<font color="#FF0000">PROTESTER HONORS VETS II</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb 16 10:28:00 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I was a protester during the war. I think the war was wrong then and is now. A country should go to war only when it is threatened because war kills and maims people, including innocent people. We weren't threatened and we killed people, including innocents. Without us the war doesn't go on. <br><br>
Those people who fought in Vietnam were forced to. Whether they were drafted or not they wee forced by the draft or by the way their country raised them. I believe they were all victims. I also think the veterans should have been honored for their scrifice. They believed they were fighting for their country. The reasons they fought aren't changed because we later decide that the war was a mistake.<br><br>
I also believe that amnesty was right. Many people who left Ameica because of the war did so because of a strong moral sense that it was wrong. At some point, when your country takes the wrong path, the citizen has to stand up and be counted. There's a museum in Germany dedicated to those who did that in the thirties and forties. There aren't many people listed there. Maybe if there were more things would have been different.<br><br>
I think what we need to do most in regards to the Vietnam war is try to see the other fellows point of view and forgive. This will be much more difficult for many veterans because of what they went through. But there were many of us protesters that felt rage, that hated. Those emotions are something that we can all do without. It's long past time to be rid of them.  
